{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17540098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17540098"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:50:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:50:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16737"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16737"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.32,0.13,0.14,0.38]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9428"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109061"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9428","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9428"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16737"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91427"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8981"},{"type":"tags","id":"9673"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22293"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30644"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43652"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109061"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of chest tightness and shortness of breath that is worst on Monday mornings and improves as the week progresses. She works in a cotton spinning factory and has been employed there for eight years. She has a history of hayfever for which she occasionally takes antihistamines. She does not take any other regular medications. She has never smoked.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Chest examination reveals scattered wheeze throughout both lung fields. Spirometry shows a forced expiratory volume in one second (FEV1) of 2.1 L (2.8-3.5) and forced vital capacity (FVC) of 3.0 L (3.2-4.0).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chronic bronchitis","Occupational asthma","Reactive airways dysfunction syndrome","Hypersensitivity pneumonitis","Byssinosis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of byssinosis, an occupational lung disease caused by exposure to cotton dust. The characteristic pattern of symptoms being worst on the first day back at work (typically Monday) and improving through the week is pathognomonic for this condition. The presence of reduced FEV1 and FVC on spirometry supports an obstructive pattern consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EByssinosis\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in workers exposed to cotton, flax, or hemp dust. The \u0027Monday morning phenomenon\u0027 or \u0027Monday fever\u0027 occurs because workers develop a temporary tolerance to cotton dust endotoxins during the work week. Over the weekend, this tolerance is lost, leading to an exaggerated inflammatory response when re-exposed on Monday. This response involves release of histamine and other inflammatory mediators from mast cells, along with activation of complement pathways by bacterial endotoxins present in cotton dust. As the week progresses, tolerance redevelops, explaining the improvement in symptoms. Symptoms include dyspnoea, cough, wheezing, and sometimes fever. Prolonged exposure may result in irreversible lung damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOccupational asthma\u003C/strong\u003E typically shows persistent symptoms that worsen with exposure and improve away from work, but does not show the classic \u0027Monday morning\u0027 pattern seen in byssinosis. Additionally, occupational asthma often demonstrates reversibility with bronchodilators.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypersensitivity pneumonitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an immunologic reaction to organic dusts that typically presents with fever, cough, and shortness of breath several hours after exposure. It does not show the weekly pattern characteristic of byssinosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic bronchitis\u003C/strong\u003E presents with persistent symptoms including productive cough and is commonly associated with smoking, which this patient has never done. The symptoms do not typically show the temporal relationship to work exposure seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReactive airways dysfunction syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a form of occupational asthma that develops after a single, high-level exposure to an irritant. This patient\u0027s history of gradual onset over months with a characteristic weekly pattern is not consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of byssinosis involves both prevention and treatment. Primary prevention through dust control measures in the workplace is essential, including proper ventilation systems and personal protective equipment. Treatment includes bronchodilators for symptomatic relief. Workers with persistent symptoms or declining lung function should be removed from exposure. Regular monitoring of lung function and workplace dust levels is important. The condition should be reported as an occupational illness, and workers may be eligible for compensation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Byssinosis is an occupational lung disease caused by cotton dust exposure, characterised by chest tightness and dyspnoea worse on the first day back at work.","The classic pattern of symptoms improving through the work week helps distinguish byssinosis from other occupational lung diseases.","Prevention through dust control measures and respiratory protection is essential in cotton processing industries.","The Monday morning phenomenon occurs due to loss of tolerance to endotoxins during time away from exposure."],"references":["Er M, Emri S, Demir A, Thorne P, Karakoca Y, Bilir N, et al. Byssinosis and COPD rates among factory workers manufacturing hemp and jute. International Journal of Occupational Medicine and Environmental Health. 2015 Sep 15;29(1):55\u201368.\u200c Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26489943/","Alif SM, Glass DC, Abramson M, Hoy R, Sim MR Occupational Lung Diseases in Australia. 2020 Feb. Pages 1-86. Safe Work Australia. [cited 2025 Mar 11] Available at: https://www.safeworkaustralia.gov.au/sites/default/files/2020-08/Occupational%20lung%20diseases%20in%20Australia%202006-2019.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91427"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16737"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91427"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-16T19:29:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-16T19:33:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9428"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109061"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"g